The test ran close to midnight. In SQL, when casting TIME to any other temporal type, the current date is added. The engine receives the actual date at some point in time, and the test creates its expected value at a different time. When these two events occur on distinctly different days, they cause the testing to fail. To address this, we need to assert that the real value is either this day or the next day, resulting in an unattractive generalization.
